{{Concept | Name=Play-by-Email | Guid=3015-13415 | Deck=A correspondence-based multiplayer option in several turn-based computer games throughout the 1990's and 2000's, which makes use of electronic mail systems. | Characters= | Concepts= | Franchises= | Games=Games/Advanced_Civilization,Games/Empire_Wargame_of_the_Century | Locations= | Objects= | People= }}
<div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":[],"background":[]}' />
==Overview== Play-by-email ("PBeM") is a [[Concepts/Asynchronous_Multiplayer|correspondence-based multiplayer]] option in certain turn-based computer games throughout the 1990's and 2000's that make direct use of electronic mail systems. Unlike most modern types of correspondence-based multiplayer, PBeM does not rely on a centralized web service (which can render the multiplayer unusable in the event the service goes offline or becomes discontinued). While players can manually coordinate in many [[Concepts/Hotseat|hotseat]]-based games by sending and receiving game saves as email attachments, games with dedicated PBeM modes go a step further by coordinating and moderating it from within the games themselves. In addition, certain games have special PBeM functionality, such as [[Games/Advanced_Civilization|Advanced Civilization]] having each player submit their turn to the host player in a way so that everybody's turn is resolved simultaneously. The name can also refer to using email in traditional pen-and-paper/board [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Play-by-mail_game "play-by-mail"] ("PBM") games.

{{Concept | Name=Research Action | Guid=3015-13492 | Aliases=Metroidbrainia,Knowledge Game | Deck=A subgenre of Search Action where instead of having progress stymied by lacking a certain ability or skill it's blocked off until the player gains the knowledge needed to solve a type of puzzle, the tutorial/instructions for which might be found elsewhere. The Witness, Toki Tori, and Antichamber are all examples of Research Action. | Characters= | Concepts=Concepts/Puzzle,Concepts/Search_Action,Concepts/Tips,Concepts/Tutorial | Franchises= | Games=Games/Animal_Well,Games/Antichamber,Games/Blue_Prince,Games/Fez,Games/Full_Bore,Games/Outer_Wilds,Games/Return_of_the_Obra_Dinn,Games/The_Roottrees_are_Dead,Games/The_Witness_2016,Games/Toki_Tori_2,Games/Tunic | Locations= | Objects= | People= | Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/ignore_jpg_scale_super/0/30/2818942-the%20witness_20160116102744.png}}
<div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":{"file":"2818942-the witness_20160116102744.png","path":"0\/30\/","mime":"image\/png","sizes":"square_medium,square_tiny,scale_tiny,scale_super,ignore_jpg_scale_small,scale_small,scale_kubrick,scale_large,scale_medium,ignore_jpg_scale_medium,ignore_jpg_scale_super,square_mini,scale_avatar,screen_kubrick,screen_medium,square_avatar,square_small","caption":"Screenshot from The Witness"},"background":{"file":"3765508-8708768090-Outer.jpg","path":"2\/23093\/","mime":"image\/jpeg","sizes":"scale_super,scale_medium,square_medium,square_tiny,square_small,screen_kubrick_wide,screen_kubrick,scale_tiny","caption":"Screenshot from Outer Wilds"}}' />
==Overview== A Research Action game might present a puzzle or riddle that the player would have no clue how to parse if it's their first playthrough. Instead, they're tasked with exploring the vicinity like they might a [[Concepts/Search_Action|Search Action]] game in order to find a hint or a guide as to how to solve it. This might involve symbols that have yet to be explained or techniques that have yet to be imparted to the player, but would otherwise be something they could be capable of doing right from the outset (as in, no power-ups would need to be acquired first). Typically a Research Action game is built like a Search Action, potentially (but not always) with a map to consult and multiple areas to visit, and the player learns and applies information on how the game works rather than acquiring upgrades. The subgenre also includes logical deduction games where the player might receive a pertinent piece of information to an earlier conundrum, thus allowing them to solve that case and acquire some sort of reward that might include information for a different case. This back and forth aspect is key to the Research Action subgenre; games where cases/puzzles are solved sequentially might not necessarily qualify.
